05918nam a22007455i 9781400859467DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20141988nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)999373532  a97814008594677 a10.1515/97814008594672doi  a(DE-B1597)447292  a(OCoLC)922702186  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDS643.5 7aHIS0480002bisacsh04a959.8/0222191 aFriend, Theodore, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Blue-Eyed Enemy :bJapan against the West in Java and Luzon, 1942-1945 /cTheodore Friend.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©1988  a1 online resource (364 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Legacy Library ;v90800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Tables -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations and Transliterations -- tIntroduction. Liberators and Oppressors in Southeast Asia -- t1. Dependence and Development Under Dutch and American Rule -- t2. Expression and Repression Under Dutch and American Rule -- t3. Japan as Successor Empire -- t4. Expectation and Mobilization in Java and Luzon -- t5. Toward a Republic: Indonesia -- t6. Transition Republic: The Philippines -- t7. Encounters in the Asian Family -- t8. Assistance and Resistance -- t9. Japanese Repression in Victory and Defeat -- t10. Revolution in Java -- t11. Binational Restoration in Luzon -- tConclusion: Dynamics of Empire and Liberation -- tThe Sources: A Bibliographic Essay -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Blue-Eyed Enemy is a comprehensive account of the interwoven histories of the three major archipelago-nations of the West Pacific during the years of the Second World War. Theodore Friend examines Japanese colonialism in Indonesia and the Philippines as an example of recurring patterns of domination and repression in that region. He depicts Japanese rule in Greater East Asia as expressive of the folly of the general who exhorted his troops "to annihilate the blue-eyed enemy and their black slaves." At the same time he clearly shows where the return of Western power aimed at new links between conqueror and conquered, or lords and bondsmen. Throughout the work one encounters an infectious sympathy for those afflicted by imperialism and racism from whatever source, at whatever time.The book is based on documentary research in Japan, Indonesia, and the Philippines, as well as in the United States and the Netherlands, and on over one hundred interviews with major actors and key observers of the era. The analysis balances an eclectic use of social science perspectives with a humanistic concreteness, and leads to new understanding of leaders like Sukarno and Hatta, Jose P. Laurel and Benigno Aquino, Sr., and Generals Yamashita and MacArthur. As comparative tropical history, it elucidates the contrasting cultural traditions and political psychologies of Indonesia and the Philippines and explains why 1945 was a year of dramatic contrast: "reoccupation" and revolution for the first country, and "liberation" and restoration for the latter.Originally published in 1988.The Princeton Legacy Library uses the latest print-on-demand technology to again make available previously out-of-print books from the distinguished backlist of Princeton University Press. These editions preserve the original texts of these important books while presenting them in durable paperback and hardcover editions. The goal of the Princeton Legacy Library is to vastly increase access to the rich scholarly heritage found in the thousands of books published by Princeton University Press since its founding in 1905.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / A